The density of a moving object is not a Lorentz invariant quantity. In the rest frame of the meter stick (frame S), the linear density is \(\rho_0 = m_0 / L_0\), where \(m_0\) is the rest mass and \(L_0\) is the proper length. In another inertial frame \(S'\) moving with velocity \(v\) relative to S along the stick's length, the length is contracted: \(L' = L_0 / \gamma\), where \(\gamma = 1/\sqrt{1 - v^2/c^2}\). The mass in \(S'\), if interpreted as relativistic mass (energy/\(c^2\)), is \(m' = \gamma m_0\), leading to a density \(\rho' = m'/L' = \gamma^2 \rho_0\). Even if using rest mass, \(\rho' = m_0 / L' = \gamma \rho_0\). Both differ from \(\rho_0\). For orientations not parallel to the motion, the transformation still yields a different density in general. Thus, density measurements are frame-dependent.

\boxed{\text{No, observers in other inertial frames will not agree with the measurement.}}

